sting TODO
==========

Open items and ideas.  Nothing here is a promise; it is a place to record
intent so it is not lost.  Items are roughly ordered by severity within each
section.  Security reports go to the address in README, not here.

Correctness
-----------

  * KeyboardInterrupt during proc.communicate() leaks the gisp child.
    backend.py only catches OSError before calling proc.kill(), so Ctrl-C while
    gisp is grinding through Argon2id propagates straight past and leaves the
    subprocess running with the passphrase descriptor still open.  cli.main
    catches the interrupt and exits, orphaning it.

  * write_bytes mishandles a symlinked output.  _is_regular_target uses
    os.stat, which follows the link, so a symlink to a regular file takes the
    atomic-rename path -- but os.replace then replaces the symlink itself
    rather than its target.  The check and the action disagree about what the
    path means.  Decide which behaviour is wanted and make both agree.

  * Repeated options silently take the last value.  "--stego-key a
    --stego-key b" is accepted and uses b, which in a tool where a wrong
    stego-key is designed to be indistinguishable from no payload means the
    user gets the generic miss message and no hint why.  Every other conflict
    (--stego-key vs --stego-key-file, --passphrase-fd vs --passphrase-file) is
    a hard error; these should be too.  Repeating -p/-m likewise forwards
    --opslimit to gisp twice and relies on its last-wins behaviour.

  * --ratio is accepted and silently ignored by --extract.  It is meaningful
    only for --hide and --capacity; reject it elsewhere.

  * --passphrase-fd 1 and 2 collide with the pipes Popen creates.  _run_gisp
    sets stdout=PIPE and stderr=PIPE, so the child's descriptors 1 and 2 are
    those pipes and pass_fds cannot preserve the caller's.  gisp would read the
    passphrase from a pipe write-end.  Reject 1 and 2 up front; note also that
    _positive_int is named for a positivity it does not enforce, accepting 0.

  * tools/highlight-payload crashes with a traceback on a trailing flag.  The
    hand-rolled parser calls bare next(it), so "--radius" with no value raises
    StopIteration out of main.

  * The BrokenPipeError handler may still emit shutdown noise.  cli.main closes
    sys.stdout, but the interpreter's final flush can print "Exception ignored
    in: <_io.BufferedWriter...>".  The usual remedy is an os.dup2 onto
    /dev/null.  Unconfirmed -- reproduce before changing anything.

  * Open-mode FLAGS and RESERVED are written but never read.  _parse_header
    ignores bytes 4-5, so a future container revision cannot be detected: a
    hypothetical v3 payload would be misparsed as v2 rather than refused.

Security and design
-------------------

  * The stego-key is passed in argv, where it is visible in ps output and
    shell history.  gisp's own secret has --passphrase-fd; sting's has no
    --stego-key-fd, and neither the usage text nor sting(1) warns that
    --stego-key-file is the only safe form.

  * Keyed header placement depends only on the stego-key and the usable-sample
    count.  _header_pos_key mixes in the key material but not the per-image
    seed, unlike _payload_pos_key, so every image of a given size embedded
    under one stego-key puts its header in the identical slots.  An adversary
    holding several such images can correlate the touched-sample sets across
    them without the key -- a partial erosion of exactly the "nothing to
    recognise" property keyed mode is sold on.  Mixing the seed into the header
    keys is not possible directly (the seed lives in the header), so this needs
    thought: a two-stage locator, or accepting and documenting the limit.

  * locate_gisp hardcodes ~/Scripts/gisp/src/gisp, a personal checkout path
    shipped in installed code.  For a tool whose security rests entirely on a
    specific vetted backend, silently accepting a binary from a user-writable
    home directory is also a weaker default than the surrounding docstring's
    careful reasoning about explicit backends implies.

  * cli.main has no catch-all.  MemoryError, or anything Pillow and NumPy raise
    that is neither OSError nor ValueError, reaches the user as a raw traceback
    with filesystem paths in it.

Performance
-----------

  * Carrier.usable is always materialised, and for L and RGB carriers it is
    merely arange(npix * channels) -- an int64 array up to 1 GB at the sample
    cap, holding no information at all.  Even with an alpha channel the per-
    channel parts are already individually sorted, so the np.sort over their
    concatenation is avoidable O(n log n) work.  This is now the dominant
    memory cost, which constants.py acknowledges but treats as a fact of life
    rather than as the thing to fix.

  * read_bytes slurps the whole input before any size check runs, so the
    MAX_CARRIER_SAMPLES guard protects against a large decoded image but not
    against a large file.

Refactoring and internal cleanup
--------------------------------

  * tools/highlight-payload is a second, divergent implementation of the
    extract path.  It imports the privates _header_slots and _payload_slots,
    then reimplements _parse_header, _resolve_stego_key (including its
    CRLF-stripping rules) and MODE_LAYOUT's channel counts.  Four independent
    drift risks; a container-format change silently breaks the tool.  Give it a
    supported entry point in stinglib instead.

  * carrying_pixels and _pixel_coords in highlight-payload are the same
    function, differing only by an np.unique.

  * Mode validation is duplicated between _normalise_mode and Carrier.__init__,
    with two differently worded messages for one condition; the second is
    unreachable for anything the first admits.

  * _resolve_stego_key lives in cli.py but is a stego-layer concern -- which is
    why highlight-payload had to copy it.  It belongs beside stego_material.

  * capacity_bytes(ratio, header_bits=HDR_BITS) has a default that is wrong for
    keyed mode, and every real caller passes the argument.  The default exists
    only to be a latent bug; drop it.

  * _run_gisp's stdin selection is convoluted: a three-way branch, a caller
    passing "None if passthrough else b''", and "stdin is subprocess.PIPE" --
    an identity comparison on an int that works only via CPython's small-int
    cache.  The input_bytes/stdin_passthrough pair encodes one tri-state across
    two parameters.

  * parse_args is a ~75-line if/elif chain.  The kdf_opts and ceil_opts
    pass-through groups are pure table data and would collapse to a dict.

  * Options is a bare class with thirteen attributes, no validation and no
    __repr__.  A dataclass would say the same thing in a third of the space.

  * constants._program_name() runs at import time off sys.argv[0], so importing
    stinglib as a library picks up the host program's name for every
    diagnostic sting subsequently prints.

Repository hygiene
------------------

  * Nine .pyc files are tracked in git and there is no .gitignore.  They churn
    on every Python version bump, and "make clean" removes __pycache__ -- so
    running the documented clean target stages nine deletions.

